  "opinion": "As a carpenter in Philadelphia with three kids and a background that’s rooted in the practical world of hands-on work, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly chip away at people’s confidence. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theory—it’s the quiet anxiety that someone might feel when they’re told they’re ‘not good at math’ or ‘not built for science.’ For me, it’s the moment a young girl in my neighborhood hesitates to ask a question in class because she’s worried her teacher thinks she’s ‘just not smart enough.’ It’s real, it’s personal, and it’s something we all need to address. But how? Well, in my experience, the answer starts with small, tangible actions. Like when I encourage my own kids to explore math through building things—using wood, measuring, and problem-solving in the workshop. That’s how you break down the fear: by connecting abstract ideas to something you can touch and see. In a world where STEM fields often feel inaccessible to those who don’t have the right tools or the right mindset, the solution isn’t about grand gestures but about creating spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes. I’ve found that listening—truly listening—to those who feel the weight of these stereotypes is the first step. And as a Buddhist, I’ve learned that patience and understanding are the keys to change. So yes, we should address stereotype threat in STEM. Not with top-down mandates, but with the kind of quiet, consistent support that builds trust over time.",
